According to Inside Climate News, farmers are more than 25% of greenhouse gas emissions. They can be way more than 25% of the solution.

Stop adding greenhouse gasses to the atmosphere and poisoning groundwater/streams/oceans with nitrate runoff by using anaerobic digesters to turn animal and crop wastes into methane to offset natural gas/propane;

Use the wastes from the digesters to grow algae for biodiesel to offset petrodiesel;

Find the gene in Asparagopsis taxiformis (a tropical seaweed) that makes bromoform--adding just 2% of Asparagopsis  to cattle's diet might reduce their output of methane by 99%!--insert that gene into the algae we will grow for biodiesel, and after you've pressed the oils out, feed the remnant carbs/protein/vitamins/minerals to the ruminants, reduce their methane burps, and they will grow 15% faster on the same feed;

Pyrolyze all of the waste woody biomass we can come up with, to make wood vinegar (good for plants, bad for bad bugs and some weeds), pyrolysis oils for fuel, and char. Incorporate the char into the soil to store water and nutrients for crops, and its carbon stays sequestered for millennia (Google Terra Preta); 

And where soils need sweetening, use crushed silicate rock (basalt) instead of limestone (enhanced weathering). Lime adds carbon to the atmosphere. Silicates suck it out. And if you chose the right rock to crush, you can add all kinds of plant nutrients at the same time.

Both of these last two measures can hugely improve soil and its productivity while sequestering (worldwide) gigatons of carbon. Farmers/foresters have been strip mining the soil. Caring for it as above will restore it, and can triple production of depleted soils just as Earth goes from three times too many mouths to feed, to four, then five....

And farmers/foresters can save the world (or help huge) while improving their soils, crops, and bottom lines. How many wins in a row do you need?
